# Mechanical Design Philosophy

The machine was developed as a long-term DIY engineering and learning project focused on CNC systems, electronics integration, firmware configuration and mechanical design.

As the project was developed using limited personal resources and primarily as a hobby and educational platform, considerable effort was dedicated to optimizing manufacturing processes, material selection and component acquisition while maintaining acceptable mechanical performance.

During an internship process at EAFIT University in Medellín, Colombia, conversations with the CNC laboratory machine operator provided valuable practical insight into industrial CNC machine design principles. A strong emphasis was placed on the importance of recirculating ball screws to minimize backlash and improve positional accuracy.

After researching the topic further, the importance of mechanical tolerances, rigidity and backlash reduction became evident, especially within the limitations commonly present in DIY CNC developments.

For this reason, 1605 recirculating ball screws were implemented on all machine axes in an effort to reduce backlash and improve motion precision.

## Prototyping Strategy

Multiple laser-cut MDF prototypes were manufactured during early development stages due to their significantly lower manufacturing cost and rapid fabrication time.

This allowed validation of:

* Structural dimensions
* Axis positioning
* Mechanical clearances
* Assembly procedures
* Motion system integration

before proceeding to the fabrication of the final RH steel structural components.

The MDF prototyping stage proved extremely valuable for identifying mechanical issues early while reducing material waste and manufacturing costs.

## Structural Material Selection

RH steel was selected as the primary structural material mainly due to budget limitations and local material accessibility.

Although RH steel adds considerable weight compared to aluminum-based CNC structures, the additional mass contributes positively to vibration damping and overall rigidity.

The disadvantages associated with the increased structural weight include:

* Higher moving mass
* Increased mechanical stress
* Greater structural flexion forces
* More demanding alignment procedures

However, for this specific project, the added rigidity and lower manufacturing cost were considered acceptable trade-offs.

## Workspace Optimization

The machine dimensions were intentionally designed to fit within the footprint of a standard desk workspace.

This decision provided several advantages:

* Easier integration into small workspaces
* Lower material consumption
* Reduced manufacturing costs
* Improved accessibility during assembly and maintenance
* Better suitability for hobby and laboratory environments

while still maintaining enough working area for PCB prototyping, acrylic machining and medium-sized parts.

## Modular Design

The machine was designed using independent mechanical modules to simplify manufacturing, assembly and future upgrades.

The system is divided into:

* Machine bed and transmission module
* Gantry module
* X-axis carriage module
* Z-axis module

This modular approach allows individual sections of the machine to be modified or redesigned without requiring a complete reconstruction of the system.

## Manufacturing Process

Laser cutting was used extensively during both MDF prototyping and RH steel fabrication stages.

The structural steel plates were laser-cut according to CAD designs; however, some hole tolerances were affected by laser cutting clearances that were not fully considered during the design phase.

As a result, certain mounting holes required the implementation of larger diameter fasteners to compensate for excessive clearance and maintain proper mechanical stability.

Several structural alignment corrections also became necessary during assembly due to distortions introduced by welding processes.

Machine squaring and alignment remain one of the primary areas for future improvement.

## Mechanical Challenges

Like many DIY CNC developments, the project presents several common engineering challenges, including:

* Structural flexion caused by machine weight and machining forces
* Mechanical alignment complexity
* Welding-induced dimensional deviations
* Motion system tolerances
* Gantry squaring adjustments

Despite the machine weight, vibration levels have remained relatively controlled due to the rigidity and damping effect provided by the steel structure.

Backlash reduction has been significantly improved through the use of recirculating ball screws compared to lower-cost transmission alternatives.

## Components and Motion System

Several critical mechanical components were acquired through commercial suppliers such as AliExpress in order to reduce manufacturing complexity and improve reliability.

These include:

* Stepper motor mounts
* Linear shaft supports
* Linear shafts
* BK/BF supports
* Sensors
* Stepper motors
* Spindle system
* Motion accessories

Current linear shaft configuration:

* Z-axis: 12 mm
* X-axis: 16 mm
* Y-axis: 20 mm

The larger Y-axis shafts were selected due to the higher structural load requirements of the machine.

The CNC controller interface was acquired through ELECROW, following the recommendations and hardware ecosystem proposed by Bart Dring for FluidNC systems.

## Maintenance and Accessibility

The motion system and linear components remain externally accessible, simplifying inspection, cleaning and lubrication procedures.

Although this exposes the system to dust and debris contamination, it considerably improves maintenance accessibility and reduces servicing complexity.

## Scalability and Future Upgrades

One of the primary advantages of DIY CNC platforms is their scalability and adaptability.

Virtually any subsystem may be upgraded or redesigned, including:

* Spindle systems
* Motor configurations
* Drivers
* Bearings
* Linear systems
* Controllers
* Firmware interfaces

However, such modifications typically introduce secondary engineering consequences requiring additional redesign, recalibration or structural reinforcement.
